depend on each other or on the carry chain directly. The carries depend on gens, but gens only depend on x/y inputs.\n\nLet me also check propagates: `prop_05` and `prop_20`. `prop_05 = AND(partial_05, carry_04)`. `prop_20 = AND(partial_20, carry_19)`. After swap: `AND(partial_05, carry_04) -> prop_20`. This would feed into `OR(gen_20, prop_20) -> carry_20`. No cycle since prop_05 depends on carry_04 which is upstream of bit 20.\n\nHmm wait, what about `prop_20 -> carry_20 -> ... -> carry_04`? No, carry_04 is upstream — it doesn't depend on anything from bit 20+. So no cycle.\n\nBut would the rules catch this? Rule 4: AND gates must feed into OR. `AND(x05, y05) -> gen_20`. Is `gen_20` used in any OR? `OR(gen_20, prop_20) -> carry_20`. Yes! So it passes. And `AND(x20, y20) -> gen_05`. Is gen_05 used in OR? `OR(gen_05, prop_05) -> carry_05`. Yes! So both pass Rule 4.\n\nThese are same-role swaps where both wires play the same structural role (both are AND outputs feeding OR gates). The rules can't distinguish them. This IS the case the rules miss.\n\nSo for the 6-flagged-wires path, I need to fix the 3 known pairs and then search for the 4th pair. The performance concern is:\n1. Pairing up 6 wires: 15 pairings × simulation → fast\n2. Finding the 4th pair: ~214 wires → 214^2/2 ≈ 23K pairs × simulation\n\nEach simulation is O(220 gates) and I do ~52 test cases. So 23K × 220 × 52 ≈ 263M operations. That might be ~3-5 seconds. With the dependency cone optimization, I can reduce the candidate set significantly.\n\nLet me update my test to use realistic swaps and also optimize the simulation further."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1113,"cache_read_input_tokens":66328,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1113},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7be18000-7ded-496e